The paper discusses steganographic techniques for SIP, which is a protocol used for VoIP. This falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) as the paper is discussing covert channels and hiding information. Additionally, the paper also discusses the amount of data that can be transferred in signalling messages, which falls under the category of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The paper also mentions multimedia (cs.MM) as VoIP involves transmitting audio and video data. Information theory (cs.IT) is also relevant as the paper discusses the amount of data that can be transferred. Finally, distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC) may also be relevant as VoIP involves distributed computing.
